'''''Plagiopholis nuchalis''''', commonly known as the '''Assam mountain snake''', is a [[species]] of snake in the [[Family (biology)|family]] [[Colubridae]].<ref>{{cite web|title=''Plagiopholis nuchalis ''|url=http://www.ubio.org/browser/details.php?namebankID=202445|publisher=uBIO|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=''Plagiopholis nuchalis ''|url=http://animaldiversity.ummz.umich.edu/accounts/Plagiopholis_nuchalis/classification/|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> The species is [[Endemism|endemic]] to [[Asia]].

==Geographic range==
''P. nuchalis'' is found in [[China]] ([[Yunnan]]), [[Laos]], [[Myanmar]], and [[Thailand]]. It may possibly also be found in [[India]] ([[Assam]]) and [[Vietnam]].<!-- Specimens from Yunnan have been described as the [[subspecies]] ''Plagiopholis nuchalis kunmingensis''. (''Oligodon kunmingensis is a synonym of ''Plagiopholis blakewayi'', fide RDB, 10 December 2018) --><ref name=RDB>{{cite web|title=''Plagiopholis nuchalis ''|url=http://reptile-database.reptarium.cz/species?genus=Plagiopholis&species=nuchalis|publisher=The Reptile Database|accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref>

==Description==
A small snake, ''P. nuchalis'' may attain a total length of {{convert|45|cm|in|abbr=on}}, which includes a tail {{convert|5.5|cm|in|abbr=on}} long. [[Dorsum (anatomy)|Dorsally]] it is blackish brown, with many of the [[dorsal scales]] edged with black. On the neck there is a broad black chevron, pointing forward, to which the [[Specific name (zoology)|specific name]], ''nuchalis'', refers. Ventrally it is yellowish, marked with black.<ref>Smith MA (1943).</ref>

==Reproduction==
''P. nuchalis'' is [[Oviparity|oviparous]].<ref name=RDB/>

